<tr>
<th style="background:#ccccdd; font-size: 95%; padding: 0 5px 0 5px;">
<div class="noprint plainlinksneverexpand navbar" style="background:none; padding:0; font-weight:normal;; font-size:xx-small;">This box: <a href="/wiki/Template:Economics_sidebar" title="Template:Economics sidebar"><span title="View this template" style="">view</span></a>&#160;•&#160;<a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Economics_sidebar" title="Template talk:Economics sidebar"><span title="Discussion about this template" style="">talk</span></a>&#160;•&#160;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Economics_sidebar&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Economics_sidebar&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow"><span title="Edit this template" style=";">edit</span></a></div>
</th>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Behavioral economics</b> and <b>behavioral finance</b> are closely related fields that have evolved to be a separate branch of economic and financial analysis which applies scientific research on human and social, <a href="/wiki/Cognitive_bias" title="Cognitive bias">cognitive</a> and emotional factors to better understand <a href="/wiki/Economic" title="Economic" class="mw-redirect">economic</a> <a href="/wiki/Decision_making" title="Decision making">decisions</a> by consumers, borrowers, investors, and how they affect <a href="/wiki/Market_price" title="Market price">market prices</a>, <a href="/wiki/PE_ratio" title="PE ratio" class="mw-redirect">returns</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Allocation_of_resources" title="Allocation of resources">allocation of resources</a>.</p>
<p>The field is primarily concerned with the bounds of <a href="/wiki/Rationality" title="Rationality">rationality</a> (selfishness, self-control) of <a href="/wiki/Homo_economicus" title="Homo economicus">economic agents</a>. <a href="/wiki/Behavioral_model" title="Behavioral model" class="mw-redirect">Behavioral models</a> typically integrate insights from <a href="/wiki/Psychology" title="Psychology">psychology</a> with <a href="/wiki/Neo-classical_economics" title="Neo-classical economics" class="mw-redirect">neo-classical economic theory</a>. <a href="/wiki/Behavioral_Finance" title="Behavioral Finance" class="mw-redirect">Behavioral Finance</a> has become the theoretical basis for <a href="/wiki/Technical_analysis" title="Technical analysis">technical analysis</a>. <sup id="cite_ref-kirkpatrick_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-kirkpatrick-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Behavioral analysts are mostly concerned with the effects of <a href="/wiki/Market" title="Market">market</a> decisions, but also those of <a href="/wiki/Public_choice" title="Public choice" class="mw-redirect">public choice</a>, another source of economic decisions with some similar biases towards promoting self-interest.</p>
